 1856, the sixth of Henry and Mary Corse Lyman's seven children. He practiced as a notary public in Montreal — a Quebec civil-law legal profession distinct from his father Henry's role as advocate in the Lyman Class law firm. He lived to age eighty-two, dying in 1938 and buried at Mount Royal Cemetery with his parents."},{"number":2,"category":"family","header":"First documented within-tree cousin marriage 1882","body":"Albert Clarence Lyman married Florence Anna Whitney on June 28, 1882 in Montreal — the first within-tree cousin marriage documented in the Hooker descendants project. Albert and Florence were both Hooker descendants through different children of Hannah Stiles Lyman: Albert's father Henry Lyman and Florence's grandmother Hannah Lyman Mills were siblings. Their three children carry two independent paths of descent from Thomas Hooker."}],"slug":"albert-lyman-1856"},"HD4213":{"id":"HD4213","former_ids":["X01254"],"is_placeholder":false,"has_descendants_documented":false,"bio":{"first_name":"Florence","middle_name":"Anna","last_name":"Lyman","maiden_name":"Whitney","married_names":["Lyman"],"gender":"female","display_name":"Florence Anna Whitney Lyman"},"birth":{"year":1856,"month":1,"day":10,"state":"Canada East","country":"Canada"},"baptism":{},"death":{"year":1920,"month":2,"day":4},"residence":{},"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM328","plot_notes":"Cimetière Mont-Royal Montreal — buried alongside husband Albert Clarence Lyman."},"classification":{"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_thomas_spouse":false,"is_talcott_spouse":false,"generation_from_thomas":9,"include_in_path_calculation":true,"descent_paths_to_thomas":1,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"is_progenitor":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"parents":{"father_id":"X01591","mother_id":"HD0584"},"number_of_marriages":1,"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"HD0588","date_year":1882,"date_month":6,"date_day":28,"location_city":"Montréal","location_state":"Quebec","location_country":"Canada","end_type":"death","end_year":1920,"children_ids":["HD4219","HD4220","HD4221"]}],"education":[],"career":[],"military_service":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"artworks":[],"tags":["canada_migration","cousin_marriage"],"research_tags":[],"cross_connections":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"family","header":"First documented within-tree cousin marriage 1882","body":"Florence Anna Whitney married her first cousin once removed Albert Clarence Lyman on June 28, 1882 in Montreal — the first within-tree cousin marriage documented in the Hooker descendants project. Both were great-grandchildren of Hannah Stiles Lyman through different children: Florence Anna descended through Hannah Stiles's daughter Hannah Lyman Mills and granddaughter Hannah Jane Mills Whitney, while Albert Clarence descended through Hannah Stiles's son Henry Lyman. Their three children carry two independent paths of descent from Thomas Hooker."}],"quotes":[],"sources":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"slug":"florence-lyman-1856"},"X02824":{"id":"X02824","former_ids":[],"is_placeholder":false,"has_descendants_documented":false,"bio":{"title":"Colonel","first_name":"George","middle_name":"Stephen","last_name":"Cantlie","suffix":"D.S.O.","married_names":[],"gender":"male","display_name":"Col. George Stephen Cantlie","photo_url":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dc5clrqtw/image/upload/v1778704423/georgecantile_xugoef.jpg","photo_notes":"Portrait of Col. George Stephen Cantlie (1867-1956), D.S.O. of the Black Watch."},"birth":{"year":1867,"country":"Canada"},"baptism":{},"death":{"year":1956,"country":"Canada"},"residence":{},"burial":{},"classification":{"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_thomas_spouse":false,"is_talcott_spouse":false,"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_paths_to_thomas":0,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"is_progenitor":false,"is_easter_egg":true},"notable":{"is_notable":true,"notable_category":["military","history"],"notable_blurb":"WWI Black Watch commander, 'Dear Wee Celia' war","primary_url":"https://americanaristocracy.com/people/george-stephen-cantlie","primary_url_label":"American Aristocracy — George Stephen Cantlie"},"parents":{},"number_of_marriages":1,"marriages":[{"children_ids":["I00647"],"marriage_number":1}],"education":[],"career":[{"role":"Original Commanding Officer (Lt-Col)","organization":"42nd Battalion (Royal Highlanders of Canada / Black Watch), Canadian Expeditionary Force","location":"France","start_year":1914,"end_year":1916,"notes":"Original commanding officer of the 42nd Battalion CEF, Royal Highlanders of Canada (Black Watch). Served as commander until the end of 1916."},{"role":"Commanding Officer (organizer)","organization":"20th Reserve Battalion","start_year":1916,"end_year":1918,"notes":"Organized the 20th Reserve Battalion and commanded it until 1918."},{"role":"Pre-war Service","organization":"5th Royal Scots (Royal Highlanders of Canada)","location":"Montréal","end_year":1914,"notes":"Served with the 5th Royal Scots before WWI."}],"military_service":[{"war":"World War I","war_id":"WAR007","rank":"Lieutenant-Colonel (later Colonel)","rank_start":"Lt-Colonel","rank_end":"Colonel","rank_year_start":1914,"rank_year_end":1918,"unit":"42nd Battalion (Royal Highlanders of Canada / Black Watch), CEF; Distinguished Service Order 1916","notes":"Distinguished Service Order awarded Dec 29, 1916 / Jan 1, 1917 (London Gazette). Service file: B1473-S056. Survived war. Suffered what was then called battle fatigue; sent home 1917."}],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"tags":["wwi","canada_migration","distinguished_service_order"],"research_tags":[],"cross_connections":[{"type":"in_law","related_id":"HD4221","display_label":"married his daughter Giana"}],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"military","header":"Original CO of Canada's Black Watch in WWI","body":"Lt.-Col. George Stephen Cantlie was the original commanding officer of the 42nd Battalion, Royal Highlanders of Canada (the Black Watch) in the Canadian Expeditionary Force — taking the battalion to France in 1914 and commanding it through the end of 1916. He earned the Distinguished Service Order awarded December 1916. After his battalion command he organized and led the 20th Reserve Battalion until 1918, when battle fatigue sent him home."},{"number":2,"category":"art","header":"Pressed flowers for baby Celia from the trenches","body":"During his command across the battlefields of France in 1915 and 1916, Col. Cantlie picked flowers from bivouac fields and pressed them into letters home to his infant daughter Celia — born 1913, only one year old when he shipped out. He wanted her to have something to remember him by should he not return. Over three hundred such letters were preserved by his daughter and granddaughter; ten of them, written during the Battle of the Somme with pressed daisies, poppies, yellow roses, and heather, form the basis of the touring War Flowers exhibition at the Canadian War Museum."}],"quotes":[],"sources":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"slug":"george-cantlie-1867"}},"burialCemetery":{"id":"CEM328","name":"Cimetière Mont-Royal","city":"Outremont","state":"Montréal Region","country":"Canada","founded":1852,"wikipedia_url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mount_Royal_Cemetery","primary_url":"https://www.findagrave.com/cemetery/639448/cimeti%C3%A8re-mont-royal","hooker_connections":["HD0580","HD0583","HD0584","HD0585","HD0586","HD0587","HD0588","HD4178","HD4182","HD4183","HD4187","HD4188","HD4189","HD4190","HD4191","HD4192","HD4194","HD4196","HD4198","HD4199","HD4210","HD4211","HD4213","HD4214","HD4219","HD4220","HD4221","HD4228","HD4229","I00630","I00631","I00632","I00634","I00640","I00641","I00643","I00645","I00646","I00647","X01250","X01251","X01252","X01253","X01591","X02825","I01230"],"notes":"Cimetière Mont-Royal (Mount Royal Cemetery), Outremont, Montreal QC. Major Protestant cemetery founded 1852 on the slopes of Mount Royal. Burial site of multiple members of the Lyman family — Hannah Stiles Lyman's descendants who became prominent Montreal druggists, lawyers, and civic figures: Elisha Lyman Jr. (with his three wives memorialized together), Henry Lyman, Mary Corse Lyman, Henry Herbert Lyman (later commemorated here after death on the Empress of Ireland 1914), Albert Clarence Lyman, Frederick Stiles Lyman, Edith Mary Louise Lyman, and others."},"institutionsById":{},"crossConnections":[]}